================================================================================
REVIEWED SUMMARY (reviewed — unverified items marked NOT VERIFIED)
================================================================================

C++ emTmpFile.h: temporary file path management with IPC-based dead
directory cleanup.

Zero emCore consumers. 2 files outside emCore use this type —
emTmpConvModel.h and emTestContainers.cpp.

Entire class is unported. No Rust equivalent exists.

C++ provides two classes:
  emTmpFile        — creates a temp file path via emTmpFileMaster,
                     auto-deletes on destruction.
  emTmpFileMaster  — per-process temp directory under a common path.
                     Runs an emMiniIpcServer to respond to liveness
                     pings. Dead directories from crashed processes
                     are cleaned up by pinging their IPC servers.

Rust has no consumer of this functionality. The tempfile crate is
in Cargo.lock (test dependencies only). tests/behavioral/file_selection.rs
has a custom TempDir struct (lines 7-26) used only in tests.

Open question 1: "Will emTmpConv need the full IPC cleanup mechanism?"
  Cannot be answered without knowing emTmpConv's requirements. The
  tempfile crate auto-deletes on Drop, which handles the normal case.
  The IPC dead-directory cleanup handles the crash case (process dies
  without running destructors). Whether emTmpConv needs crash resilience
  is a design decision.

Open question 2: "Does Rust emMiniIpc support the liveness-ping pattern?"
  Rust emMiniIpc (emMiniIpc.rs) provides:
    emMiniIpcServer — StartServing, StopServing, IsServing, GetServerName
    emMiniIpcClient::TrySend — send message to a named server
  These are the same building blocks C++ uses. The protocol logic
  (ping a server, if no response then delete its directory) would
  need to be implemented on top of these.
  NOT VERIFIED: whether the Rust emMiniIpcServer handles concurrent
  pings correctly or has the same timeout behavior as the C++ version.
